          <!-- Model Answers -->
          <div class="reveal-section fade-in-up">
            <button class="reveal-btn" id="reveal-answers-btn">Show Model Answers</button>
            <div class="reveal-content" id="model-answers" hidden>

              <div class="model-grade-section">
                <h5 class="model-grade-label model-grade-label--achieved">Q1 — Achieved</h5>
                <div class="answer-card">
                  <p>
                    The primary environmental cue is <strong>photoperiod</strong> (day length).
                    Photoperiod is more reliable than temperature because it changes with
                    mathematical precision each year — the number of daylight hours on any given
                    date is identical year after year. Temperature, by contrast, fluctuates
                    unpredictably (e.g. warm spells in autumn, cold snaps in spring). An animal
                    that relied on temperature alone might migrate too early or too late in
                    unusual years.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="model-grade-section">
                <h5 class="model-grade-label model-grade-label--achieved">Q2 — Achieved</h5>
                <div class="answer-card">
                  <p>
                    The pineal gland secretes <strong>melatonin</strong>. Melatonin is secreted
                    during <strong>darkness</strong> (scotophase). On long days (short nights),
                    the duration of the melatonin pulse is short. On short days (long nights),
                    the duration of the melatonin pulse is long. The hypothalamus "reads" the
                    duration of the melatonin pulse to determine the time of year.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="model-grade-section">
                <h5 class="model-grade-label model-grade-label--achieved">Q3 — Achieved</h5>
                <div class="answer-card">
                  <p>Three reasons lipids are more suitable than carbohydrates for non-stop migration:</p>
                  <ol class="numbered-reasons">
                    <li><strong>Higher energy density:</strong> Lipids provide 39 kJ per gram, compared to 17 kJ/g for carbohydrates — more than twice the energy for the same mass. For a bird carrying all its fuel, this dramatically extends range.</li>
                    <li><strong>Anhydrous storage:</strong> Fat is stored without water, whereas glycogen (stored carbohydrate) requires 3–4 g of water per gram stored. If a kuaka stored its fuel as glycogen, its departure mass would be 5–8× greater — too heavy to fly.</li>
                    <li><strong>Metabolic water production:</strong> Fat oxidation produces 1.07 g of water per gram of fat burned. During non-stop oceanic flights with no access to fresh water, this metabolic water prevents dehydration.</li>
                  </ol>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="model-grade-section">
                <h5 class="model-grade-label model-grade-label--merit">Q4 — Merit</h5>
                <div class="answer-card">
                  <p><strong>(a)</strong> The digestive organs (stomach, intestines, liver) shrink because the kuaka does not eat during its 8–9 day non-stop flight. Carrying these organs at full size would add unnecessary mass, increasing the energy cost of flight and reducing the bird's range. The mass saved can be redirected to fuel (fat) and flight muscle. Proteins from the shrinking organs can also be recycled as a supplementary fuel source during the final stages of flight. Meanwhile, flight muscles grow because they must sustain continuous powered flight over 12,000 km — larger muscles produce more thrust and have greater endurance capacity.</p>
                  <p><strong>(b)</strong> Two specific flight muscle changes:</p>
                  <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li><strong>Increased mitochondrial density:</strong> More mitochondria per muscle fibre means greater capacity for aerobic respiration, specifically β-oxidation of fatty acids. This allows the muscle to extract energy from fat at a faster rate, supporting the sustained power output needed for continuous flight.</li>
                    <li><strong>Increased myoglobin concentration:</strong> Myoglobin is an oxygen-binding protein in muscle tissue that acts as an oxygen store and facilitates oxygen delivery from blood to mitochondria. Higher myoglobin concentration ensures adequate O₂ supply to sustain aerobic fat metabolism even at high metabolic rates during flight.</li>
                  </ul>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="model-grade-section">
                <h5 class="model-grade-label model-grade-label--merit">Q5 — Merit</h5>
                <div class="answer-card">
                  <p>
                    Kuaka undergo several pre-migratory physiological changes:
                  </p>
                  <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li><strong>Hyperphagia and fat deposition</strong> — body mass nearly doubles, with fat reaching 55% of body mass. Adaptive because fat is the sole energy source for the 8–9 day non-stop flight; without sufficient reserves, the bird would starve en route.</li>
                    <li><strong>Pectoral muscle hypertrophy</strong> — flight muscles enlarge by ~30%. Adaptive because larger flight muscles produce more thrust, enabling sustained powered flight over 12,000 km.</li>
                    <li><strong>Gut, liver, and kidney atrophy</strong> — digestive organs shrink by up to 25%. Adaptive because the bird does not eat during migration, so these organs are dead weight. Reducing mass lowers the energy cost of flight and increases range.</li>
                    <li><strong>Heart enlargement</strong> — cardiac muscle increases. Adaptive because sustained aerobic exercise requires high cardiac output to deliver oxygen to flight muscles.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <p>
                    <em>For full Merit:</em> Each change must be <strong>linked to an adaptive
                    explanation</strong> using biological terminology. Simply listing the changes
                    without explaining their function would be Achieved level.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>

              <div class="model-grade-section">
                <h5 class="model-grade-label model-grade-label--excellence">Q6 — Excellence</h5>
                <div class="answer-card">
                  <p><strong>(a)</strong> The results demonstrate that migration timing is controlled
                  by an <strong>endogenous circannual rhythm</strong> — an internal biological clock
                  with a period of approximately one year. Because the birds showed cyclical patterns
                  of fat deposition and Zugunruhe even in the absence of any seasonal environmental
                  cues, the timing programme must be <strong>internally generated</strong>, not
                  simply a response to external conditions.</p>

                  <p><strong>(b)</strong> The fact that the free-running period was ~10–11 months
                  (not exactly 12) shows that the endogenous clock is <strong>imprecise</strong>.
                  In nature, <strong>photoperiod acts as a Zeitgeber</strong> — an external
                  time-giver that <em>entrains</em> (synchronises) the circannual clock to the
                  real 12-month calendar. Without this calibration, the clock gradually drifts
                  out of phase with the seasons. Photoperiod corrects this drift each year,
                  ensuring the animal migrates at the biologically optimal time.</p>

                  <p><strong>(c)</strong> Having both systems provides a <strong>robust, flexible
                  timing mechanism</strong>:</p>
                  <ul class="feature-list">
                    <li>The <strong>endogenous clock</strong> ensures the animal begins preparing for migration even before environmental conditions change noticeably. This is critical because physiological preparation (hyperphagia, muscle growth) takes weeks — waiting for obvious environmental signals would leave insufficient time to prepare.</li>
                    <li>The <strong>Zeitgeber</strong> prevents the clock from drifting, which would cause migration timing to shift progressively earlier each year (by ~1–2 months per cycle). Mismatched timing — arriving at breeding grounds before food is available, or departing too late and encountering storms — would reduce fitness.</li>
                    <li>The dual system also provides <strong>flexibility</strong>: secondary Zeitgebers (temperature, food availability) can fine-tune departure date within the window set by photoperiod, allowing some adjustment to local conditions. This is adaptive in the context of year-to-year variation and long-term climate change.</li>
                  </ul>
                  <p>
                    <em>For Excellence:</em> The answer integrates endogenous and exogenous
                    control, explains the adaptive advantage of each, and discusses how they
                    interact. It goes beyond description to <strong>evaluate</strong> the system.
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>

            </div>
